# functions to show an image
def imshow(img):
    img = img / 2 + 0.5     # unnormalize
    npimg = img.numpy()
    plt.imshow(np.transpose(npimg, (1, 2, 0)))
    plt.show()

2. KNN CLASSIFIER¶

As our first approach, we will develop what we call a Nearest Neighbor Classifier. The nearest neighbor classifier will take a test image, compare it to every single one of the training images, and predict the label of the closest training image.

In [5]:
### test k means
from classifiers import KNN

Note that following 3 cells will take a lot of time to execute on an ordinary pc. That is because KNN classifier is very inefficient, it has to compare each image in train with each image in val

In [6]:
train_loader, val_loader, train_size, val_size = get_data_loaders("data/data.csv", "data/train/", batch_size = "knn")
k = KNN(train_loader,val_loader,train_size,val_size)

3. Convolutional Neural Network¶

Neural Networks receive an input (a single vector), and transform it through a series of hidden layers. Each hidden layer is made up of a set of neurons, where each neuron is fully connected to all neurons in the previous layer, and where neurons in a single layer function completely independently and do not share any connections. The last fully-connected layer is called the output layer and in classification settings it represents the class scores. Convolutional Neural Networks take advantage of the fact that the input consists of images and they constrain the architecture in a more sensible way. In particular, unlike a regular Neural Network, the layers of a ConvNet have neurons arranged in 3 dimensions: width, height, depth. (Note that the word depth here refers to the third dimension of an activation volume, not to the depth of a full Neural Network, which can refer to the total number of layers in a network.)

      (conv1): Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn1): BatchNorm2d(256, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
      (relu): ReLU(inplace=True)
      (conv2): Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn2): BatchNorm2d(256, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
    )
  )
  (layer4): Sequential(
    (0): BasicBlock(
      (conv1): Conv2d(256, 512, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(2, 2), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn1): BatchNorm2d(512, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
      (relu): ReLU(inplace=True)
      (conv2): Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn2): BatchNorm2d(512, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
      (downsample): Sequential(
        (0): Conv2d(256, 512, kernel_size=(1, 1), stride=(2, 2), bias=False)
        (1): BatchNorm2d(512, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
      )
    )
    (1): BasicBlock(
      (conv1): Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn1): BatchNorm2d(512, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
      (relu): ReLU(inplace=True)
      (conv2): Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1), bias=False)
      (bn2): BatchNorm2d(512, eps=1e-05, momentum=0.1, affine=True, track_running_stats=True)
    )
  )
  (avgpool): AdaptiveAvgPool2d(output_size=(1, 1))
  (fc): Linear(in_features=512, out_features=196, bias=True)
)

# functions to show an image
def imshow(img):
    img = img / 2 + 0.5     # unnormalize
    npimg = img.numpy()
    plt.imshow(np.transpose(npimg, (1, 2, 0)))
    plt.show()

4. Topological data analysis : Mapper algorithm¶












In [21]:



    


%%latex 
A computational method for extracting simple descriptions of high dimensional data sets is a Mapper algorithm:
Let $X$ be a point cloud (data set) and we have a function $f:X \to \mathbb{R}$.
Assume that we have $N$ points in $X$ whose outputs are known for the function $f$.
Also, we assume that it is possible to compute inter-point dinstances between the points in the data.
Let $I$ be the range of the function $f$ restricted to the $N$ points and let $S$ be the covering of $I$.
We begin by dividing $S$ into a smaller intervals $(S_i)$ which overlap.
This gives us two parameters $l_i$ the length of $S_i$ and $p_{ij}$ the fa
perceptange overlap between successive intervals.
Now for each $S_i$ we find a set $X_j = \{x | f(x) \in S_j\}$ s.t. $X_j \subset X$. The set $\{X_j\}$ forms a cover of $X$, and $X \subset \cup_j X_j$.
For each smaller set $X_j$ we find clusters $\{X_{jk}\} $.
We treat each cluster as a vertex in our reeb graph and draw an edge between vertices whenever $X_{jk} \cap X_{lm} \neq \emptyset$ i.e. the clusters corresponding to vertices have non-empty intersection.



    















    







A computational method for extracting simple descriptions of high dimensional data sets is a Mapper algorithm:
Let $X$ be a point cloud (data set) and we have a function $f:X \to \mathbb{R}$.
Assume that we have $N$ points in $X$ whose outputs are known for the function $f$.
Also, we assume that it is possible to compute inter-point dinstances between the points in the data.
Let $I$ be the range of the function $f$ restricted to the $N$ points and let $S$ be the covering of $I$.
We begin by dividing $S$ into a smaller intervals $(S_i)$ which overlap.
This gives us two parameters $l_i$ the length of $S_i$ and $p_{ij}$ the fa
perceptange overlap between successive intervals.
Now for each $S_i$ we find a set $X_j = \{x | f(x) \in S_j\}$ s.t. $X_j \subset X$. The set $\{X_j\}$ forms a cover of $X$, and $X \subset \cup_j X_j$.
For each smaller set $X_j$ we find clusters $\{X_{jk}\} $.
We treat each cluster as a vertex in our reeb graph and draw an edge between vertices whenever $X_{jk} \cap X_{lm} \neq \emptyset$ i.e. the clusters corresponding to vertices have non-empty intersection.

from sklearn.datasets import fetch_openml
data = fetch_openml('diabetes').data.tolist()
out = mp.Mapper(lens = "PCA", clusterer = "DBSCAN", n_rcover = [100, 3], clusterer_params = (0.1,5))
out.write_to_json(data)

from dataloaders import get_datasets
import mapper as mp
#from sklearn.datasets import fetch_mldata
from sklearn.datasets import fetch_openml
import torch
import numpy as np

train_set,valset = get_datasets("data/med_data.csv",'data/train')
train_size = len(train_set)
train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_set,
                                           batch_size=len(train_set),
                                           shuffle=True,
                                           num_workers=25,
                                           drop_last=True)
it_train = iter(train_loader)
train_images, train_labels, train_paths = it_train.next()
train_images = np.squeeze(train_images.numpy().reshape((train_size, 3*128*128))).tolist()
data = train_images.tolist()
out = mp.Mapper(lens = "PCA", clusterer = "DBSCAN", n_rcover = [100, 3], clusterer_params  = (0.1,5))
out.write_to_json(train_images)
